\subsection{Server-Side Code: Express.js Routing}

\begin{lstlisting}[style=nodejs, caption=Express Server Setup (app.js)]
import express from "express";

const app = express();
const port = 3000;

// Serve static files from 'public' folder
app.use(express.static("public"));

// Route for opening page
app.get("/", (req, res) => {
    res.render("open.ejs");
});

// Route for main menu page
app.get("/main", (req, res) => {
    res.render("main.ejs");
});

// Route for Simon game
app.get("/simon", (req, res) => {
    res.render("Simon.ejs");
});

// Route for Dice game
app.get("/dice", (req, res) => {
    res.render("dicee.ejs");
});

// Route for Drum Kit
app.get("/drum", (req, res) => {
    res.render("Drum.ejs");
});

// Route for Tic-Tac-Toe
app.get("/ttt", (req, res) => {
    res.render("ttt.ejs");
});

// Start the server
app.listen(port, () => {
    console.log(`Listening to the port: ${port}`);
});
\end{lstlisting}

\newpage
\chapter{Testing and Evaluation}

This chapter presents the testing strategies applied during the development of the web-based mini-game platform.

\section{Testing Strategy}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Unit Testing:} Individual JavaScript functions for game logic
    \item \textbf{Integration Testing:} Interaction between front-end and back-end
    \item \textbf{User Interface Testing:} Layout responsiveness and visual feedback
    \item \textbf{Cross-Browser Testing:} Consistent behavior across browsers
\end{itemize}

\section{Testing Scenarios and Results}
\begin{table}[h!]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{|l|l|l|}
\hline
\textbf{Test Case} & \textbf{Expected Result} & \textbf{Outcome} \\ \hline
Simon Game Sequence Match & Correct level progression & Passed \\ \hline
Tic-Tac-Toe Win Detection & Declares correct winner or draw & Passed \\ \hline
Dice Roll Randomness & Varies on each click & Passed \\ \hline
Drum Kit Key Mapping & Plays corresponding sound & Passed \\ \hline
Responsive Layout & Adapts to different screen sizes & Passed \\ \hline
Navigation Between Games & Loads correct game route & Passed \\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\caption{Test Cases and Results}
\end{table}

\section{Performance Evaluation}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Load Time:} Quick due to lightweight design
    \item \textbf{Responsiveness:} Instant response to user inputs
    \item \textbf{Resource Usage:} Efficient memory usage
\end{itemize}

\section{User Feedback}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Positive feedback on clean UI and smooth gameplay
    \item Suggestions for visual design improvements
\end{itemize}

\section{Limitations Identified}
\begin{itemize}
    \item No persistent storage or scoring history
    \item Single-player functionality only
    \item Manual testing limits scalability
\end{itemize}

\newpage
\chapter{Results}

This chapter presents the results obtained from the implementation and testing.

\section{Functional Outcomes}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Simon Game:} Memory-based color and sound sequence game
    \item \textbf{Random Dice Roll:} Two-player dice simulation
    \item \textbf{Tic-Tac-Toe:} Turn-based strategy game
    \item \textbf{Drum Kit:} Interactive soundboard
\end{itemize}

\section{Performance Metrics}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Fast load time
    \item Low latency interaction
    \item Cross-platform compatibility
\end{itemize}

\section{User Experience Feedback}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Simple and clear UI
    \item Smooth transition between games
    \item Enjoyable gameplay
\end{itemize}

\section{Achievement of Objectives}
All defined goals were successfully achieved:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Functional, interactive web-based platform
    \item Applied front-end and back-end technologies
    \item Engaging user experience
\end{itemize}

